Here is the minimal working Drush command class (DrushCommands-based):

```php
<?php

namespace Drupal\my_module\Drush\Commands;

use Drush\Attributes as CLI;
use Drush\Commands\DrushCommands;

#[CLI\Command(name: 'my-module:hello')]
class MyModuleCommands extends DrushCommands
{
    #[CLI\Argument(name: 'name', description: 'Name to greet')]
    #[CLI\Option(name: 'upper-case', description: 'Output name in uppercase')]
    public function hello(string $name, array $options = ['upper-case' => false]): void
    {
        $greeting = $options['upper-case'] ? strtoupper($name) : $name;
        $this->io()->success("Hello, $greeting!");
    }
}
```

Key points:
- Place in `src/Drush/Commands/` (not `src/Commands/`)
- Extend `Drush\Commands\DrushCommands`
- Use `use Drush\Attributes as CLI;` and `#[CLI\Command(...)]`, etc.
- Use `$this->io()->success()`, `$this->io()->error()`, `$this->io()->table()` for user output
- **No `drush.services.yml` needed** for command discovery
- Autowiring is supported: inject services via constructor (e.g., `__construct(private LoggerInterface $logger)`) — Drush will resolve them

