Example command that accepts either `--file` or `--inline-content`, but requires at least one:

```php
<?php

namespace Drupal\my_module\Drush\Commands;

use Drush\Attributes as CLI;
use Drush\Commands\DrushCommands;

#[CLI\Command(name: 'my-module:import-data', aliases: ['m-import'])]
#[CLI\Argument(name: 'name', description: 'A short descriptive name for the import job.')]
#[CLI\Option(name: 'file', description: 'Path to the CSV file to import.')] #[CLI\Option(name: 'inline-content', description: 'Raw CSV content as a string.')] public function importData(string $name, array $options): void {
  $hasFile = !empty($options['file']);
  $hasInline = !empty($options['inline-content']);

  if (!$hasFile && !$hasInline) {
    $this->io()->error('Either --file or --inline-content must be provided.');
    return;
  }

  if ($hasFile && $hasInline) {
    $this->io()->error('Only one of --file or --inline-content may be used.');
    return;
  }

  $content = $hasFile ? file_get_contents($options['file']) : $options['inline-content'];

  // Process $content...
  $this->io()->success("Import job '{$name}' queued successfully.");
}
```

**Notes:**
